Life resolution #1: less explaining, more being. On that note:

1. hi! I have a really long name but people like to call me Nabi ( or other augmentative or diminutive versions of that if you speak Portuguese like Nabinha or Bão). I’ve lived a full, beautiful and sometimes scary life which led to me develop the tendency to compartmentalize. It is my commitment to myself to unify the dots.
2. I’ve been living a double life of artist/performer and part-time Quantum healing practitioner. This is me coming out of the closet ! 
3. I went on a shamanic s&xu@lity retreat and discovered I am an absolute baby and know nothing about nothing. I also know a lot. And the people I met there humbled me to my knees while also honoring me with my crown. I learned my emotions are emotions and not the stories behind them. 
4. These are the women who raised me, the main ones at least. One pushed me out and the other held her. I like this picture because they look like a couple and it makes me feel like their masculine and feminine polarities are inverted. 
5. I’ve been sitting on and hoarding SO MUCH music that I honestly cannot wait to share ( no , really, I’ve been holding so tight it hurts my fingers )
6. I don’t like when people think I’m American.
7. Dancing ( and full body orgasms) are the easiest ways to connect to the divinity inside. The taboo around movement and sacral energy is a disservice to humanity. I encourage everyone to use dance and s&xu@lity as medicine ( meaning utilize it with consciousness!) 
8. I did my makeup this day and it made me happy ( it was oily though)

“I got to learn how disco and rock and roll were kind of like these two competing rebel music or alternative music [styles]. The face of rock and roll was the white man; the face of disco music was the Black woman.” For Be, the “most gratifying part” of Daisy Jones was being able to “tell a truthful story to the best of our abilities” about the queer, Black women who owned the underground club scene and the clubbers who were able to find a joyful sense of community. “That was a safe space for Black, Brown, Latino people to feel joy, and that’s really the birth of disco music,” she says. “It started in underground, marginalized spots, and predominantly from music that was coming from immigrants, and [there was] that transition from RnB and soul into what later became disco music.”
.

8. A disclaimer about my future: I will build the illusion myself, and then I will use all my tools to destroy it.

When I think about who I want to be in the world, what imprint I want to leave on people and on earth, I’m brought to the beginning: innocence. To cultivate a beginner’s mindset in all areas of my life, means to be humble enough to want to keep  learning. To be brought back to a state of play where mistakes are welcomed. 

I watch the cycles turn and I know every now and then an end comes to call me. I’m learning how to make a conscious choice and present my naked body to life and say: “here’s my old skin, please take it”. The other way around seems to involve some big shock that catapults me into having no choice but to learn how to let things die. I’d like to learn how to die consciously.

I’d like to use this platform to walk my talk as much as I can and lovingly destroy the illusions it may create between us. 

If you’re down for it as much I am: you have no idea how happy that makes me! If not, there will be plenty of music, beautiful photos and travel experiences for your eyes and ears. But I promise the other way around is much more intimate and fulfilling. Drop a ⚡️ if you agree! 📸: @meredithadelaide

THE CROSSING

Part of me has crossed.
We communicate through songs
Outcries and tornados
That at every moment
Inhabit the bridge that links us

She tells me about her adventures
And how the home of our hearts
Gets bigger every day

How under her feet
She grew such 
Fierce and joyful roots 
That even two distant countries 
Unite like the leaf of a vine

We love each other.
And she reminds me everyday 

We make love
Cradled by the winds of our story
And we climax to the sound of our own voice
And the potency of our womb.

We dream the IMPOSSIBLE.
And as we awaken
We hear the calling 
Of the first steps:

One
At 
A
Time

Until we prepare for the big jump
Where I finally cross the bridge 
And right there in air
I steal her a kiss

A kiss 
For all of eternity.

A minha vida é a celebração de muitas. Dia Internacional da Mulher Negra Latino - Americana e Caribenha. 

A black, latina and Caribbean woman.

How many do I know? How many am I?
There’s Tereza de Benguela,my grandma Christine and even Sister Nancy… but somewhere amongst these forgotten names, is my own. 

I sit down next to one of the images of Sebastião Salgado, depicting the sad eyes of a black woman around a tiny squared window.  The title: “ Other Americas”. I think to myself: “ if she’s the other, then so am I”. Invisible, but present. What if she knew how much her invisibility shined on my own light, gave me solid grounds to grow and fortified my impetus ? Would she smile? I dare to say she would. 

Because as I rise from the ashes and unravel my truth out in the open, they all live with me. A life they could only dream of.

My name is Nabiyah Be, I am a black , Latina and Caribbean woman and i am happy and free. And maybe, just maybe not fearing all the facets of freedom is our biggest victory yet.

The face of nutrition. Been home for almost two months and as it always goes, there have been more moments in full presence than photos at hand. All I know is that hope is a muscle and that there are always hidden gems ready to be found in our motherland. Eu mesma, só agradeço.

Estava na areia como um um aviso que aconteceu. Os olhos dela eram fixos como que o de uma serpente verde que via o vendaval passar e subir depois de tudo que viveu. 

Enquanto Caetano cantava, se lembrava da cobra de olhos verdes que a habitava e que hoje mesmo não se cansava de mudar de pele pra achar ainda mais brilho no seu próprio olhar. 

É com esse brilho - que nasceu e que morreria-  que ela seguia com as pernas fortes que a foram dadas, ancorando e se tornando os olhos do próprio furacão. 

Eu me tenho. 

📸 @mariadelagala
It’s Virgo season and I gotta laugh at my self-criticism y’all! Here’s a girl learning how to play the drums passing through your timeline.

Lately all I’ve wanted is to wash myself clean in the poetry of my mother tongue, sing my memories out loud and tell my loved ones my heart is dripped in seeing beauty through their eyes. 
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
A few things I’m learning right now:
- living with my heart open at all costs.  Specially when that also means feeling more fear, rage and sadness. I will not numb myself in the face of challenges.
- Making decisions from a place of love and courage. Seems simple but have you noticed how much of your life has been constructed to protect yourself from your feelings of helplessness and despair? 
- It can be simpler
